Finally, the item "Grow a flytrap or sunflower" is a top seller with more than 16,000 items sold.

22
00:00:58.840 --> 00:00:58.840


23
00:00:58.840 --> 00:01:00.040


24
00:01:00.040 --> 00:01:07.360
To further investigate the data, you will use more elaborate calculations and methods for inventory analysis.

25
00:01:07.360 --> 00:01:16.000
In this second part, you will deal with the average value of inventory, Inventory turnover, and ABC analysis.

26
00:01:16.000 --> 00:01:16.000


27
00:01:16.000 --> 00:01:16.000


28
00:01:16.000 --> 00:01:18.640
The average value of inventory is often used

29
00:01:18.640 --> 00:01:24.120
to know the value of an item during a specific period that accounts for seasonal fluctuations.

30
00:01:24.120 --> 00:01:29.800
It is calculated as the average of the total cost at the start and end of a particular period.

31
00:01:29.800 --> 00:01:29.800


32
00:01:29.800 --> 00:01:31.200


33
00:01:31.200 --> 00:01:34.920
Inventory turnover is an efficiency ratio that shows how

34
00:01:34.920 --> 00:01:39.680
often a company uses its supply of goods during a given period.

35
00:01:39.680 --> 00:01:39.680


36
00:01:39.680 --> 00:01:43.880
It can be calculated by dividing COGS over the average value of inventory.

37
00:01:43.880 --> 00:01:43.880


38
00:01:43.880 --> 00:01:45.160


39
00:01:45.160 --> 00:01:49.320
ABC analysis is a technique that helps you prioritize inventory

40
00:01:49.320 --> 00:01:55.280
management by classifying your items into three categories: A, B, and C.

41
00:01:55.280 --> 00:01:55.280


42
00:01:55.280 --> 00:01:55.280


43
00:01:55.280 --> 00:01:58.120
You can do ABC analysis in four steps.

44
00:01:58.120 --> 00:02:04.240
First, you need information on the revenue of your items; then,

45
00:02:04.240 --> 00:02:08.440
you calculate the percentage they represent from the total revenue.

46
00:02:08.440 --> 00:02:11.880
Once you have the percentages, you must sort the column in

47
00:02:11.880 --> 00:02:15.360
descending order to allow the computation of a cumulative increase.

48
00:02:15.360 --> 00:02:23.080
Finally, you classify the items according to a rule of how much they cover of total revenue.

49
00:02:23.080 --> 00:02:28.000
A items will cover up to seventy percent of total revenue, B items will cover

50
00:02:28.000 --> 00:02:33.280
the following twenty percent, and C items will represent the remaining percentage.

51
00:02:33.280 --> 00:02:33.280


52
00:02:33.280 --> 00:02:34.440


53
00:02:34.440 --> 00:02:36.520
You have done great work so far.

54
00:02:36.520 --> 00:02:41.640
In the following exercises, you will focus on more elaborate analyses, such as contrasting

55
00:02:41.640 --> 00:02:48.840
revenue among years, calculating an efficiency ratio, and classifying the importance of your items.

56
00:02:48.840 --> 00:02:48.840


57
00:02:48.840 --> 00:02:48.840


58
00:02:48.840 --> 00:02:54.960
These new measures will help you see the data in a better way to find new approaches to solving the problem.

59
00:02:54.960 --> 00:02:56.200


60
00:02:56.200 --> 00:02:56.200


61
00:02:56.200 --> 00:02:59.080
It is time to dig for more information with these new metrics.

62
00:02:59.080 --> 00:03:01.680
Let's do it!

